article.headline: Nebraska 73, Yale 64
article.story: LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- Wes Wilkinson came off the bench to lead Nebraska with 14 points and the Cornhuskers beat Yale 73-64 in the John Thompson Basketball Challenge on Saturday. The Huskers held Yale to just seven points in the final 6 1/2 minutes to secure the victory. Nebraska (2-0) led by as many as nine late in the first half. But an 8-0 run helped Yale (1-1) cut the Husker lead to two at the half. Wilkinson hit his first shot of the second half to push the lead to four, Nebraska's biggest advantage until near the end of the game. Yale took the lead for the first time in the second half on Matt Kyle's jumper with 15:45 left. The Bulldogs went up by three on Sam Kaplan's basket with 11:59 remaining that made the score 50-47. Nebraska regained the lead for good on Joe McCray's jumper that put the Huskers in front 59-57 with 4:45 left. A pair of Jason Dourisseau free throws and an Alex Maric jumper pushed the Nebraska lead to six with 1:30 left. Yale was able to cut the lead to four on Casey Hughes' layup with 36 seconds left. But Nebraska hit seven free throws to seal the win. Both teams struggled from the field. Nebraska hit just 34 percent of its shots. Yale hit 39 percent. Nebraska won the game at the foul line, making 28 of 36 free throws. Yale made five of its eight foul shots. Dourisseau had 13 points and McCray added 12 in the win for Nebraska. Kaplan led Yale with 19 points.
